===Etymology===
From {{etyl|fr}} {{term|pragmatique}} < {{etyl|LL.}} {{term|pragmaticus||relating to civil affair; in Latin, as a noun, a person versed in the law who furnished arguments and points to advocates and orators, a kind of attorney}} < {{etyl|grc}} {{term|πραγματικός|tr=pragmatikós||active, versed in affairs|lang=grc}} < {{term|πρᾶγμα|tr=pragma||a thing done, a fact|lang=grc}}, in plural {{term|πράγματα|tr=prágmata||affairs, state affairs, public business, etc.|lang=grc}} < {{term|πράσσειν|tr=prassein||to do|lang=grc}} (from whence English {{term|practical|lang=en}}).

